         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne ¶ 24 June 1885. ¶ To his Excellency  ¶  ¶ Capt. Alfr. Moloney, C.M.G., ¶ Governor of Gambia &amp;c. ¶ Sir...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">85.06.24</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Alfred Moloney </p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">F86/6828, unit 136, VPRS 3992/P inward registered correspondence, VA 475 Chief Secretary's Department, Public Record Office, Victoria.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter registered as B84/1631.</p>
               </note>Melbourne</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">24 June 1885.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">To his Excellency <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Capt. Alfr. Moloney, C.M.G.,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Governor of Gambia &amp;c.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have the honor to acknowledge your Excellency's communication, dated 16. April,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See A. Moloney to M, 16 April 1885 (in this edition as 85-04-16a) , and M to G. Berry, 24 June 1885 (in this edition as <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>85-06-24a).</p>
               </note> in accordance with which I have procured on behalf of the Victorian Government for transmission through my ministerial Chief, the hon Graham Berry, Chief Secretary of Victoria, a collection of fresh seeds of such Eucalypts, as deserve trial-culture in Gambia and could be procured just now, the sending being a gift of the Government of Victoria. As regards the saline nature of the ground-water in many parts of your colonial territory I would beg to remark, that all Eucalypts are […]y<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Illegible.</seg> — MS smudged.</p>
               </note> to brackish soil; but doubtless many localities in Gambia would still be available for the culture of these important trees.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>To provide timber and fuel for places, where the humidity is saline, it will be best to choose species of Melaleuca, a few of which will grow in brackish water, for instance M. Leucadendron, M. ericifolia, M. linearifolia.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">M. linariifolia</seg>?</p>
               </note> Of these I will procure seeds purposely, and send them for transmission to the hon. the Chief Secretary here. The Melalecuas like the Eucalypts have great anti-malarian power, hence would also [be]<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">editorial addition</seg> — word omitted.</p>
               </note> for sanitary purposes a valuable acquisition to your colony and other parts of Western Africa. Some other kinds of <name key="Eucalyptus">Eucalyptus</name>-seed I hope to send later, when fresh procured. May I ask your Excellency, whether without much trouble a small quantity of fresh and well matured seeds of the Coapim-grass (<name key="Panicum%20spectabile">Panicum spectabile</name>), which is so famous for its rapid growth and nutritive property, could be obtained from your colony for test culture in Victoria</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">I have the honor to be</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>your Excellencys obedient </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
